{"key":"post-11673938","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11673938</id>\n<content>This is a bad idea that's been hashed around many, many times before and all the results are right at your fingertips in the search engine.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;First, it would take a HUGE amount of salt to raise the boiling point in the pressure cooker by even a few degrees.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Second, as already pointed out above, at 100C/212 the moisture content of the rye grains would begin evaporating out of the rye since the water in the pressure cooker isn't boiling or building pressure yet.&amp;nbsp; By the end of an hour, there would be no moisture left in your jars.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Third, even if you made a salt paste for your PC and managed to raise the temperature at a given pressure, the blowout plug which works on temperature, not pressure, would blow out.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Fourth, salt is corrosive and not something you want in your pressure vessel.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Fifth, if you're going to be using rye, you need a pressure cooker that goes to 15 psi, but many members here have succeeded with 10 psi by adding 1/3 extra time to the cycle.&amp;nbsp; Soak the grains first to hydrate them, which makes it easier to kill off the bacterial endospores in the grain.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11673945</next>\n<prev>11673931</prev>\n<first>11673773</first>\n<last>11675206</last>\n<when>1261152834</when>\n<utime>12/18/09 06:13 PM</utime>\n</post>"}